The first virtual provider is already coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile radio market in the Czech Republic is fairly mature and the Czech suppliers offer virtually all services, as they are offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classic to lower prices.
Maybe it won't wait long.
The fact that the Czech mobile operators are working at all in Europe, we have often reported on mobile.cz.
This also confirmed the ČTÚ Telecommunications Authority, which drew attention to the fact that the price for an SMS here is higher than the rest of the European Union.
Following the last steps of the European Commission in the area of roaming fees, it is likely that there will be a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile providers, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really makes a fight.
Maybe it sounds paradox, but there are three mobile networks and a penetration of more than 100% in Czech Republic.
On the other hand, mobile operators would like to argue that there is extremely much competition on the Czech market.
The President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ) Pavel Dvořák, who in the past has often said that there is no room for another provider in the Czech Republic.
It is likely that a classic provider with its own network has no more but many opportunities (by the way, he probably would not even find any frequencies).
But there is another possibility - a virtual provider.
Just the entry of the virtual provider into the mobile radio market brought a significant price reduction with it, to which the classical mobile providers also had to respond.
Before the entry of such companies as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile, there were similar voices on the UK market as in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can really be successful.
By the way, you don't have to look for examples for long.
In February this we reported on the start of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider managed to win more than 100 thousand customers and thus rise to the country's fifth largest provider.
Behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which has U:phones in Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual providers is that one can focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to function effectively, virtual providers need much less customers than a classic provider.
They do not need a relatively high cost for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers are usually like low cost companies - they offer cheap phone calls and SMS, which is often accompanied by a less extensive service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile in Britain offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a pretty good move to set a non-climatic target group.
This provider is specifically addressed to men.
"The real guy chooses Mobilking - the provider they like and trust," says David Seibert, CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, the company operator of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept could take place in the Czech Republic as well as in Poland.
The press speaker of Vodafone Miroslav Čepíký also doubted this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the service."
In Czech Republic, no chance, the mobile phone providers
However, it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile provider conquers the Czech Republic, this will not be mobile.
"We are talking about an expansion of this successful project, but the negotiations in the Czech Republic do not seem hopeful.
It will come rather to a market entry of Mobilking in other countries of our region," said Jana Studničková, a press spokesman for the Penta Financial Group.
Indirectly, she confirmed that the current mobile phone providers in the Czech Republic are not quite comfortable with this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything they can to ensure that there is no potential competitor.
Their interest in starting a virtual mobile phone provider has for a long time shown the GTS Novera group that wants to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed networks, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this option with all the Czech mobile operators.
With some of them we were already able to make progress in negotiations," said the press spokesman of the Pavel Kaidl Group.
Maybe better times come now.
Unofficial information suggests that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
Until now, however, this is surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
"At this moment, we do not assume that there is room in the Czech Republic for a full virtual provider.
The Czech market is very specific to other markets.
So far, we have not been addressed by a subject with a complex and serious project in this area," he said in his statement to Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sršeň from the Press Department of Telefónica O2.
Other suppliers also point to the specificity of the Czech market.
The press speaker of T-Mobile Martina Kemrová adds in rare agreement with the O2 statement: "We have not yet found a viable and mutually beneficial project on which to build."
And she adds: "The T-Mobile network will hardly show up a virtual provider by the end of the year.
At this point, we had to have a concrete offer to think so briefly."
Vodafone focuses on meeting the requirements of its own 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepíký believes: "For negotiations with potential virtual providers, we are open, especially in the area of cost-sharing and infrastructure.
This is exactly what we considered to be the best from the point of view of our customers.
The main strategy of Vodafone in this area is looking for a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile internet."
The responsible authorities - with their suppliers hand in hand
It is easy to understand that another provider called more competition, which would lead to lower prices and thus also to a fall in profits.
So why should such a competitor facilitate market entry?
The fact that suppliers can draw on a string, when it comes to something, also shows the long turn and turn about the origin of U:phone.
The probably strongest pressure towards ČTU went at the time when U:fon came to the market, from the company T-Mobile.
This is also evidenced by the publicly available information from the ČTU website.
Now, however, just U:phone is suitable as an argument why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová also noted: "The competitive environment of the mobile phone market has recently been strengthened by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile phone provider.
In view of the nature of the mobile radio market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new actor would have high requirements on the market itself and in particular its services."
In view of this approach by mobile operators, however, the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities is surprising.
This is not only the attitude of the Czech Republic, which unfortunately - unlike Britain and other highly developed countries - does not have the power to intervene in economic competition.
It is exclusively owned by the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (UOHS).
This, however, referred to this whole problem of his very typical attitude.
"The entry into the market of a virtual mobile provider would be possible once a contract between a mobile provider and a virtual provider has been concluded over the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far no such contract has been concluded, because the offer of potential stakeholders was probably not interesting enough for the classic suppliers," said Kristián Chalupa of the Department of External Relations of the ÚOHS in his reply to our request.
The representatives of the suppliers would not surprise such a formulation.
This is more than a matter of concern from an authority that represents consumer interests and should, among other things, ensure that no one abuses its position on the market.
In particular, when Kristián Chalupa adds: "In the rest of the world, where virtual providers are normally working, it is to be observed that their market entry has contributed to a price reduction in mobile telephone services."
However, it is likely that the pressure on the correct functioning of the market and a price reduction does not belong to the interests of the ÚOHS.
In this case, it is truly shocking that the almost already touching conformity of the three mobile phone providers emerge from their reactions.
The question of whether it really is just a coincidence is on hand.
Just like the absolutely same gas price at the tank stations, it is certainly only a coincidence and the result of a tough competition.
"The Authority has not found any indications in this case which indicate action directed against competition, and therefore it has no reason to intervene in any way on the matter.
None of the suppliers have a dominant market position, so neither does it have the corresponding increased responsibility for its market action.
The instruments needed to open the mobile phone market for virtual providers are probably also missing from the regulatory authority for telecommunications," Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points.
There is, of course, an analysis of the relevant markets, drawn up by the ČTÜ, after telecommunications from the point of view of economic competition is a single market.
On such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile providers have a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - the consent of the network operator is always necessary for the entry into the market of a virtual provider.
And the mobile phone provider - logically - has the monopoly for his network.
This means that he is necessarily taking a dominant position in a particular segment.
Even if you do not agree with this argument, it should be at least a warning for the ÚOHS that three mobile phone providers are acting similarly.
A number of interested parties (including the mentioned company GTS Novera) argue that they fall into very similar obstacles in negotiations with all suppliers.
The diversion of responsibility to the ČTU is then a fairly common trick in telecommunications services, with which the ÚOHS distances itself from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, it has not been possible to implement the newly adopted Telecommunications Act's Novelle to extend the ČTù's competence to the field of economic competition in telecommunications, even though a number of experts had promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS need to know all too well, but they probably have different interests.
It's okay if no one's looking.
Only once remains the functioning of any pseudovirtual provider, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks.
There are companies that publish their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but only partly public.
This is usually the case with companies operating in the area of multi-level marketing.
For example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies are usually only selected.
The joke is that the company acts against the operator as a classic company that orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, it then receives special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the business conditions of all Czech mobile providers prohibit similar resales.
"If there are cases that you describe, then it may be an infringement of the contractual conditions with which we will then deal, which could lead to the termination of cooperation with the company concerned," Martina Kemrová answered our question about this problem.
However, it is quite unlikely that such a thing will not happen to mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, thousands of customers may be involved.
However, no operator opposes such an action.
The activities of these companies do not cause them to miss out on profits; at the same time - unlike actual virtual suppliers - they are not affected by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav Čepíký points out possible problems: "The law allows such kinds of speculation, however, the services of these companies are used only by a very low percentage of customers.
They also have to accept that the SIM card does not run on their phone, so they cannot have full access to it as normal customers of mobile phone providers."
However, at least the ČTÚ had to do this on its own.
There is also a further question for the ÚOHS.
Do mobile providers close their eyes before such a procedure, why do they block themselves from a virtual provider?
It is to be added that the ÚOHS has quite strong powers to detect such activities, and if it does not, it does not have to satisfy the supplier's statement that they knew nothing about it and that their business conditions would prohibit this.
When Czech is no longer the most expensive
As already stressed in the text several times, the market entry of virtual providers brought a sharp price decline in the various services with them.
Practically, in all countries where virtual providers have been created, classical providers have tried to prevent their birth virtually more or less.
The arguments used by them were practically identical - a too small, or too saturated market, problems in the quality of services, etc.
In the highly developed countries, however, regulatory bodies are currently involved, not in any way the interests of mobile operators, but in the interests of their customers.
Whether by means of formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator was created, and further followed.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory authorities are throwing themselves into the whole case like a hot potato.
Based on our experience, we cannot assume that clarity in the competences in these cases is more than favorable.
But we don't throw the flint into the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider is soon to appear, the Czech mobile phone market may be moving again soon.
If a provider allows the creation of a virtual mobile phone provider, the ÚOHS will not remain inactive when it comes to rejecting other interests (to be discriminated against).
And then the Czechs will finally no longer call more expensive than the rest of Europe.
