Hepatitis: When is the doctor to visit?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed under the leading causes of death.
However, the number of infected is estimated to be hundreds of thousands, but only seven thousand are treated, which means that patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for various infectious liver diseases.
Symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and jaundice are common, but errors and diseases differ.
Depending on the breeder, the hepatitis virus is spread in two different types: hepatitis A and E by digestion (e.g. by contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C and D by blood and other body fluids (e.g. sperm, secretion or storage).
Travellers are recommended for vaccination against viruses A and B, however, there is no vaccine against the virus C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A occur approximately two to three weeks after consumption of the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by nausea, weakness, abdominal pain and vomiting.
Then the yellowing occurs on the skin and in the eyes, the chair becomes bright, the urine is dark, and the healing can take up to two or three weeks.
Around the world, about 1 million people die annually from hepatitis B-related, far more severe diseases such as liver cancer and liver cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that according to estimates, only every 10 infected people are treated with medication.
Hepatitis C may also have serious consequences: it may lead to liver cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected people don't even know about their disease because the bug destroys the liver cells in a home - in many cases the first symptoms are shown after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular checks, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease occurs more often: those who underwent a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattoos.
At present, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated at 200 million.
Since the disease is already detectable in a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to visit the home doctor at the first signs of unknown origin.
In due course, the disease is healthy, the virus can be eradicated, thus banning the risk of infection and preventing cancer.
On September 30, the World Day of Hepatitis, 2004 is the first time of patient representations worldwide.
The aim of the action is to strengthen awareness of the chronic liver inflammation caused by viruses, their emergence and the importance of early detection.
